CXXXII. AD ILLUSTREM COMITEM GORDONIUM‚ MAR- CHIONIS HUNTLAEI FILIUM, NATU MAXIMUM (1-12).

Tu modo ducebas acies, Huntleta proles, Bellatrixque tuam Gallia sensit opem. Hoste triumphato, Veneris iam vincula gestas, Et te captivum Cypria pone trahit. Niteris exemplo regum ; fortissimus Hector, Magnus et Aeacides miles Amoris erat. Mortales si forte sequi, Dis nate, recusas, In caelo superos, quos imiteris habes. Casside deposita, Veneri dedit oscula Mavors, Et pater, abiecto fulmine, dixit, Amo.

Gordon, first glory of the Scottish youth, thou whose martial virtue places thee on the pedestal oi thy father’s fame, Victory with her gilded pinions com- passed thee around‚ and the ivory caron white steeds whitled thee along. Now Love and the Graces‚ and Venus with her team of swans‚ have.begun to trip along, escorting thee to thy Lady. The Muses' aid thou needest also: as they sang erewhile thy triumphs, soon will come Hymen needing celebratIon.

2. AD EUNDEM.

Prima Caledoniae‚ Gordoni, gloria pubis, Martia quem virtus grandibus aequat avis,

Te prius auratis cinxit victoria pennis, Et vexit niveis currus eburnus equis.

Nunc Amor et Charites et iunctis Cypria cycnis, Ad dominam tecum carpere coepit iter.

Est opus et Musis: Musae cecinere triumphos Ante tuos, veniet mox celebrandus Hymen.
